Overview

  • Random normally-generated noise
  • Eye-tracking active/passive sentences
    • Additional data from Japanese
    • Auto-correlation in behaviour (why?)
    • Problems for traditional approaches
  • Permutation test
    • Simulation-based approach
    • Permute the labels and see how likely you will get the correct results by chance

On-line eye tracking data (2 seconds)

  • Variability early on will reduce strength of effect

500 ms windows

  • 1500-2000 window is now significant

Variable populations

  • Different populations have different windows
  • Japanese effect is split across two windows

Standard mixed model analysis

  • Use 500 ms windows
data$win = as.integer(-0.001+data$time/500) # divide time by 500
# aggregrate, code, and fit model
subjmeans.df = aggregate(target ~ win + lang + cond + subj, data, mean)
subjmeans.df$cwin = subjmeans.df$win - mean(subjmeans.df$win)
subjmeans.df$ceng = ifelse(subjmeans.df$lang == "English",0.5,-0.5)
subjmeans.df$cpassive = ifelse(subjmeans.df$cond == "passive",0.5,-0.5)
model = lmer(target ~ cwin*ceng*cpassive + (1 | subj), subjmeans.df)

Problem: Window variability

  • Windows can change significance of results
  • Windows are arbitrary
    • based on previous studies
    • removing autocorrelation
    • Few exact replications
  • After looking at the data, it is possible to discover reasons for using various windows
  • Different populations have different processing speeds
    • Different languages
    • Children at different ages

Problems with a mixed model analysis

  • Each window is not independent
  • Time as a randoms slope (does not capture complex effect of time)

Multiple Comparisons

  • Why not just run a t-test in several windows for the English and the Japanese data?
    • Condition x window interaction?
  • FMRI Resting state data 499 controls (Eklund, Nichols, & Knutsson, 2016)
    • null hypothesis (5% false positives)
    • 70% false positivesã€€
    • FMRI software does not adjust for multiple comparisons

One Solution: Permutation Analysis

  • Grey windows show regions where significant difference has been found

Permutation Analysis Steps

  1. Compute test statistic for each time window
  2. Cluster significant windows together
  3. For each time window, permute labels and test for significance.
    • Put maximal test statistic for trial in permutation distribution
  4. For each cluster test if the observed test statistic is less than most of the permutation distribution

Compute test statistic

  • Test statistic: linear model
  • Are active and passive different for this window?
onetime = subset(pdata,time == 400 & lang == "English")
onemodel = lm(target ~ cpassive, onetime)
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)

##  cpassive    -0.01886    0.07968  -0.237    0.814    
##  ---
print(abs(coef(summary(onemodel))[2,3]))  # get observed t value
## [1] 0.2367483
print(abs(coef(summary(onemodel))[2,4]))  # get observed p-value
## [1] 0.8142727

Compute test statistic

  • p-values are orange when > 0.05
  • p-values are black when <= 0.05

Compute test statistic: R code

  • loop over each language and each time window, and compute test statistic
timelist = unique(pdata$time)
for (l in c("English","Japanese")){
  for (t in timelist){
    # create data frame for ONE timebin for each language
    onetime = subset(pdata,time == t & lang == l)
    # do regression model on target using structure condition
    onemodel = lm(target ~ cpassive, onetime)
    # this is the t-value for structure
    targetT = abs(coef(summary(onemodel))[2,3])  # observed t-value
    targetP = abs(coef(summary(onemodel))[2,4])  # observed p-value
    # save t, p in means.df
    means.df$tstr[means.df$time == t & means.df$lang == l] = targetT
    means.df$pstr[means.df$time == t & means.df$lang == l] = targetP
  }
}
# for figure, create line where 0.2 represents p=0.05
means.df$pline = 0.2+0.1*(0.05-means.df$pstr)

  4. For each cluster test if the observed test statistic is less than most of the permutation distribution

Clustering adjacent windows

Clustering adjacent windows

  • Cluster number cnum is incremented whenever window is not significant
  • Don't change cnum when previous window and present window are significant
    • Increment when entering a significant window
cnum = 1
lastpval = 100
means.df$cnum = 1
for (l in c("English","Japanese")){
  for (t in timelist){
    onetime = subset(means.df,time == t & lang == l & cond == "active")
    pval = abs(onetime$pstr)
    if (pval < 0.05 & lastpval > 0.05 ){
      cnum = cnum + 1  # increase cluster number when entering a significant cluster 
    }
    if (pval > 0.05 ){  
      cnum = cnum + 1 # increase cluster number when not significant
    }
    lastpval = pval
    means.df$cnum[means.df$time == t & means.df$lang == l] = cnum
  }
  cnum=cnum+1  # new cluster for different languages
}

Create permutation distribution

  • create 1000 simulated experiments with permuted labels
# use only significant clusters from active
meansonlyact.df = subset(means.df, cond == "active")
sigcluster = subset(meansonlyact.df, abs(pstr) < 0.05 )
n = 1000  # number of replication in distribution
exptestvalue = data.frame()  # data frame for results of distribution
# loop over every significant cluster 
for (s in 1:length(sigcluster$time)){
  cl = sigcluster$cnum[s] # cluster number
  b = sigcluster$time[s] # time
  l = sigcluster$lang[s] # language
  onetime = subset(pdata,lang == l & time %in% b)   # one time point
  randSet = onetime   # randSet is a copy of onetime that is scrambled
  # create 1000 permuted models
  for (i in 1:n){
    # permute labels
    randSet$cpassive = sample(randSet$cpassive,length(randSet$cpassive))
    randmodel = lm(target ~ cpassive ,randSet) # predict target from structure
    t = coef(summary(randmodel))[2,3]     # extract and save t-values
    # save results
    df = data.frame(t=t,cluster=cl,time=b,lang=l,sim=i)
    exptestvalue = rbind(exptestvalue, df )
  }
}

Cluster t values

  • this is the distribution for the simulated data with random labels (null hypothesis)
sumt.df =  aggregate(t ~ lang + cluster + sim, permdist, sum)

Find maximal t-value cluster

  • Our permutation distribution only has highest 1000 t-values
# this code extracts out the maximum sum t for each simulation at each age
maxclusterdist = data.frame()
for (l in unique(sumt.df$lang)){
  for (s in unique(sumt.df$sim)) {
    # get all results for one simulation in one language
    onesim = subset(sumt.df,sim == s & lang == l)
    onesim$astruct = abs(onesim$t)
    # find max t-value
    maxrow = onesim[order(onesim$astruct,decreasing = T),]
    maxclusterdist = rbind(maxclusterdist,maxrow[1,])
  }
}
# maxclusterdist is sorted by language, so english is first 1000
emaxclusterdist = maxclusterdist$t[1:1000]
jmaxclusterdist = maxclusterdist$t[1001:2000] # japanese is rest

Removes small t-values

  • Significance is measured relative to distribution

Clusters for observed data

  • We are interested in four clusters from the observed data

Compute p-value

  • permtdist is the distribution of cluster t-values for each language
  • p-value is the proportion of values greater than observed t-value
meansonlyact.df = subset(means.df, cond == "active")
sumcluster  = aggregate(tstr ~ cnum + lang, meansonlyact.df, sum)
for (cl in unique(sumcluster$cnum)){
  bins = unique(means.df[means.df$cnum == cl,]$time)
  lan = sumcluster$lang[sumcluster$cnum == cl][1]
  tstr = abs(sumcluster$tstr[sumcluster$cnum==cl])
  # permutation t distribution depends on language
  if(lan == "English"){ permtdist = emaxclusterdist} else{permtdist=jmaxclusterdist}
  pstr = sum(abs(permtdist) > tstr, na.rm = TRUE)/length(permtdist)
  means.df$permtestp[means.df$time %in% bins & means.df$lang == lan] = pstr
   if (tstr > tlevel){ print(paste("Cluster",cl,"Observed sum t",round(tstr,3),"Proportion dist > observed (p-value)",pstr)) }
}

Permutation test is magic

  • Permutation test finds significant clusters in a data-driven way
  • All windows are compared against full distribution, so deals with problem of multiple comparison
    • More windows -> greater chance of getting big t-value
  • Dependencies between windows are captured by clusters
    • Each cluster is one processing unit
  • Different populations can have different windows (e.g., languages, age groups)

Permutation test is dangerous

  • Still no consensus about how to use it
  • When you take the maximal test statistic only, have you lost information from the smaller test statistics?
    • Definitely more conservative
    • How noisy is your data?
    • Do you expect multiple effects or just one?
  • How do we estimate subject or item random effects?
  • Complex (order is important in creating clusters)
